<br>
But we know that if powerful laser beam strikes on solid matter are applied, than the ejection of evaporated stuff could reach higher velocities. <br>
<br>
I don`t know in which degree the Eduard Teller`s experiments for creating of X-ray or Gama-ray nuclear-explosion pumped lasers succeed, but it seems to me that such for-single-use laser devices, could be usefull for orion-type applications. <br>
<br>
If the PU consist of X-laser pointed towards certain quantity of propelant ( in the shipward direction IN one and a same canister with the laser), than the propelant plasma heated by the X-ray pulse could reach miuch higher temperature(i.e. velocity, i.e. Isp) than the &quot;naked&quot; explosion debris. <br>
<br>
Combine this as a  notion with the &quot;external supply of PUs&quot; of my previous post, but please comment separatelly!  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
P.S. The gama-laser and the propelant of course could be separated, but I mean scheme where the energy PLUS the propelant aren`t onboard the craft, also gama-laser firing from billions of miles would be much more ineffective compared with such a pulsed gama-ray laser bomb, firing a dose of propelant in the closest safe and efficient distance from the explosion-interactor of the ship. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=yales>yales</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 1243<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(6/12/03 12:18 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=333.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.attbi.com/~yales/images/53invad2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: X-ray laser PUs</span><hr size=1> Karov...<br>
In an Orion, the propellent IS heated by the X-rays. The purpose of any nuclear &quot;primary&quot; is to produce a pulse of x-rays. <br>
<br>
In a typical thermonuclear device the x-rays are focused on a shell of heavy metal. This vaporizes the surface causing a &quot;rocket&quot; effect - which implodes the shell inward to compress the fusion fuel.<br>
<br>
An Orion pulse unit does the same thing, but inside-out.<br>
<br>
The &quot;primary&quot; emits a pulse of x-rays. This radiation is channeled into material which absorbs the energy and generates a shockwave that converts the propellent into a high velocity plasma.<br>
<br>
The energy of the neutrons and other particles may contribute, but I suspect that they take too long to be important. The X-rays leave the bomb at the speed-of-light and heat the material before the neutrons.<br>
<br>
I suspect that to use the energy to produce an x-ray laser may be less efficient than this direct coupling. (I don't really know.)<br>
<br>
The main value of a &quot;star-wars&quot; laser is that it can beam energy at distant targets at &quot;c&quot;.<br>
<br>
Here is an article on Ablative Laser Propulsion. <br>
Isp's of &gt;20,000 are possible. The laser may be powered with any source such as fission, fusion, wind, hydro, coal, PV, whatever..<br>
